Based on my search, here's what I found about using ExtendScript to split/cut clips in Adobe Premiere Pro using the QE DOM:

## ExtendScript and QE DOM for Splitting Clips in Premiere Pro

### Key Findings:

There's no cut function in the ExtendScript API. The QE DOM has a `razor(string, bool, bool)` method on sequence and track objects, but some developers have reported difficulty getting it to work.

### QE DOM Razor Method Example:

Here's an example of using the QE DOM razor method to add cuts at markers:

```javascript
function addCutAtMarker(marker) {
    var sqe = qe.project.getActiveSequence(); // Get the active QE sequence
    var timecode = marker.start.seconds; // Get the marker start time in seconds

    // Convert timecode to "HH:MM:SS:FF" format
    var hours = Math.floor(timecode / 3600);
    var minutes = Math.floor((timecode - (hours * 3600)) / 60);
    var seconds = Math.floor(timecode - (hours * 3600) - (minutes * 60));
    var frames = Math.floor((timecode - Math.floor(timecode)) * 24); // Assuming 24 fps
    var timecodeString = padNumber(hours, 2) + ":" + padNumber(minutes, 2) + ":" + 
                         padNumber(seconds, 2) + ":" + padNumber(frames, 2);

    // Apply the cut to all video tracks
    for (var i = 0; i < sqe.numVideoTracks; i++) {
        var videoTrack = sqe.getVideoTrackAt(i);
        videoTrack.razor(timecodeString, true);
    }

    // Apply the cut to all audio tracks
    for (var i = 0; i < sqe.numAudioTracks; i++) {
        var audioTrack = sqe.getAudioTrackAt(i);
        audioTrack.razor(timecodeString, true);
    }
}
```

### Workarounds:

If the razor method doesn't work, a workaround is to use `overwriteClip()` with one-frame media and then delete that new media immediately, which results in two cut clips but with a one-frame gap. Another workaround is adjusting `inPoint`, `outPoint`, `start` and `end` properties, though the clip's `inPoint` and `outPoint` work in "a strange nonobvious way," so testing is recommended first.

### Documentation Challenges:

Adobe has not done a complete job keeping documentation up-to-date. The api_doc.html is "woefully out-of-date," and the ExtendScript Toolkit Object Model Viewer, which provides a view into feature support, is also out-of-date.(no content)Mimicking in-timeline editing is not fully possible through ExtendScript, but you can try to mimic classical 3-point editing through a script if your marker information allows you to calculate time values for source clips.


